To study surface functional groups, we evaluated the FT-IR spectroscopy of catalyst at each step (Fig. 3
                        ). As shown in Fig. 3a, the peaks at 580 cm−1 and 770 cm−1 are related to vibrational absorption of Cu–O and Zn–O, respectively. The presence of O–H (strong and broadened at 3410 cm−1), CO (at 1655 cm−1), CC (at 1551 cm−1), and C–N (at 1217 cm−1) confirm the N-GQDs has been covered on the core of CuO/ZnO nanocomposites (Fig. 3b). From Fig. 3c, it is evident that new bands at 3419 cm−1, 2981 cm−1, 1626 cm−1, and 1042 cm−1 are coordinated with the stretching NH, CH (sp
                        3), CO, C–N, and C–O groups, respectively, denoting the successful presentation of l-proline in the CuO/ZnO@N-GQDs nanocomposites. Thus, FT-IR results correspond to those that were gotten from the XRD and EDX spectroscopy.

To estimate nanocatalyst recovery, we evaluated l-proline assisted CuO/ZnO@N-GQDs nanocomposites for model reaction in acetonitrile solvent under microwave irradiation. After the reaction time, separated nanocatalyst, washed with EtOH and water, dried, and reused again without excess purification. As well shown in Table 4
                        , l-proline assisted CuO/ZnO@N-GQDs nanocomposites could be reused for 8 periods without any remarkable loss of activity. According to the XRD graph of nanocomposite (Fig. 11
                        ), the crystalline structure was maintained after 8 cycles reused.
